<ns5556:section xmlns:ns5556="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xml:id="resources.information.technologies.java.lang.basicLanguage.yourFirstApplication.obtainingJDK">
    <ns5557:title xmlns:ns5557="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Obtaining the Latest
        Version of the Java Development Kit</ns5557:title>
    <ns5558:para xmlns:ns5558="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">The Java Development Kit (JDK) includes the compiler, the run-time system, a range of
        other tools as well as the documentation for the tools and the standard Java class
        libraries. It can be downloaded free of charge from Sun's Java site,
            <ns5559:literal xmlns:ns5559="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">http://java.sun.com </ns5559:literal> You will also find a rich resource of
        documentation, tools, class libraries and links to useful sites there.
    </ns5558:para>
    <ns5560:para xmlns:ns5560="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
        The JDK is a low-level toolkit, which does not provide any tools to make the authoring
        of Java source code productive. Instead of a standard text editor (e.g. Vi, Notepad or Kate), 
        you will typically want to use an integrated development environment (IDE), such as 
        <ns5561:emphasis xmlns:ns5561="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Eclipse</ns5561:emphasis> or <ns5562:emphasis xmlns:ns5562="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Netbeans</ns5562:emphasis> (both free software).
        These IDEs are higher-level toolkits that typically run on top of the JDK.
    </ns5560:para>
</ns5556:section>